PPOL 646 Final Project: SNAP / Food Stamp Recipients

Bill Radovich

5/17/2021




1.)


This graphic examines the lifetime of the Food Stamp Program / SNAP benefits granted to participants over the last 50 years. Significant events in the battle over welfare during this time period are highlighted. The oft-hurled stereotype of the Welfare Queen was born out of the publicised and nationally televised trial of Linda Taylor in 1974 - a political straw man that a common welfare recipient was a lazy black woman gaming the system for money - used by Ronald Reagan and anti-welfare advocates alike to pass new restrictions on welfare during the first years of his presidency - including Food Stamps. Following a hunger crisis in the mid-to-late-80s and a brief increase in benefits to recipients, welfare was reformed once again during the Clinton administration in 1996 - again heavily fueled by the welfare queen stereotype held by lawmakers. During the 2008-09 Global Recession, the Food Stamp program was heavily modified into the SNAP program and replaced references to stamps or coupon with card or EBT to eradicate semantics that were previously used in racist attacks on the program and its recipients. SNAP funding has decreased in the past decade with a Republican-controlled congress influenced by the anti-welfare Tea Party movement and deficit hawks.


2.)



The distribution of poverty across the United States is shown in the map above. The light green highlighting states in the Great Plains, New England, the Mid-Atlantic, Alaska, and Hawaii indicate these regions generally have a lower poverty rate hovering around 8-12%. Darker orange-highlighted states in Appalachia and the Sun Belt have poverty rates of up to 20% - including states like Mississippi, New Mexico, West Virginia, and Kentucky. The West Coast and Midwest are somewhere in-between. The goal of this map was to gain insight into the actual poverty rates geographically and how these relate to the histories of each state and/or region of the country.


3.)



This map displays the poverty rate for children ages 0 to 4 on the same scale as the one above. It is clear that the distribution of poverty generally remains the same across the aforementioned regions and states. In states like New Hampshire, Utah, Virginia, Wyoming, and Maryland, the poverty rate for children 0-4 still remains just above 10%. However, the same Sun Belt and Appalachian states have significantly higher rates of poverty among young children - above 30% in Mississippi, New Mexico, and Louisiana. Despite the attacks on mothers on welfare for decades, babies are more likely than adults to be in poverty and reliant on public assistance.


4.)



The average monthly SNAP cost per child vs.medium income by state shows that there is no real correlation between the two measures. Low-income states could reasonably have high SNAP costs for children because of the massive poverty rates (Mississippi, top-right corner), or low SNAP costs due to lower cost of living. The same is true for high-income states - New Hampshire ($70,986/year median income) has low SNAP costs - D.C. has moderate per child SNAP costs - and Alaskas are among the highest in the country. This can be explained by New Hampshires low wealth inequality and D.C.s high wealth inequality (measured by Gini index). Alaska, despite having the lowest Gini in the U.S., can have its high SNAP costs attributed to the cost of importing basic foods and goods into the state. The costliness to feed children on SNAP is likely influenced more by historical and/or geographic factors of the region, wealth inequality, and cost of living rather than a states income.


5.)



This interactive map aims to show the proportion of SNAP recipients whom are children, or women who are pregnant or postpartum. In most states, children make up more than half of recipients. Adult women make up around 20-25% of total SNAP recipients - including adult women who are pregnant or postpartum, who alone make up around 14%-20% depending on state. In Puerto Rico, 63.3% of recipients are children.


6.)



This donut chart highlights the massive discrepancy between the proportion of Americans outside the 50 states + DC in US Territories and American Indian Reservations and the much more significant proportion those Americans are on SNAP. American Indians living on Reservations, despite making up less than (an estimated) 0.449% of the US population in 2016, they made up an estimated 2.138% of all SNAP participants/recipients. Those living in the 5 US Territories - Guam, the Virgin Islands, American Samoa, Puerto Rico, and Northern Marianas - made up an estimated 2.154% of welfare recipients despite having 1.155% of the US population.


7.)



This graph follows the relationship between the % of Americans suffering from hunger, or food insecurity, vs.the average monthly Food Stamp / SNAP benefit per participant. Following over a decade of the Clinton and Bush Jr.administrations maintaining a relatively modest average Food Stamp benefit per participant, the Great Recession caused the worst economic crisis since 1929, and a resulting spike in hunger. Highlighted on the graph are the two data points during the Recession, where hunger remained relatively high until several years of increased SNAP benefits to Americans. This quickly fell back down after 2010, closer to where it was before the Recession.


8.)



Despite anti-welfare advocates insisting on punishing welfare recipients due to the abusers and defrauders or imposing harsh restrictions that cut off recipients, fraud from participants makes up a tiny amount of the total money spent annually on SNAP - nearly all of which goes towards food or overhead costs. Household errors made up most fraud costs in 2016 at $424 million. Agency errors cost the program $188 million and fraudulent claims cost $73 million - compared to a total program expenditure of $70.9 billion.


9.)



The purpose of this line graph is to illustrate the effect of unemployment on hunger over the past 25 years. The spike in unemployment to nearly 10% in 2009-2010 was predicated with a large increase in hunger in 2008 - possibly explained by home foreclosures from the Subprime Mortgage Crisis. While unemployment steadily decreased to below 5% by 2015, the percentage of Americans suffering from hunger didnt return to pre-Recession numbers until the end of the 2010s.


10.)



This line graph shows the trend for percentages of both low food security and population growth rate. Due to the relative economic hardship the United States has faced since the Great Recession, the resulting rise in hunger and its slow recovery, and the significant composition of children and their mothers, I expected to see a decline in the population growth rate over time if the decrease in birth rate was significant enough to drag it down. While there is no obvious correlation here, hunger and lack of appropriate nutrition to Americas mothers and children are a plausible cause for the steady decline in population growth since 1995. Factors such as higher levels of education and wider availability of birth control are also reasonable suggestions for this. In Todays context, President Joe Biden has been posited as an anti-Reagan after laying out a massive jobs plan to a Joint Session in late April 2021 to fix the COVID-19 unemployment crisis, and attacking the Trickle Down Economics that have been the standard economic policy since Reagan himself. The effects of this spending will be noteworthy in determining if a return to Big Government can rapidly and measurably reduce economic hardship, and the suffering associated.
